Respond to fines

Ernesto Carrella

July 30, 2015

Two species world

Very simple result I am showing today. Same generic coast, in this scenario there are 2 species. A red specie that is uniformly distributed all over the map and a blue specie that is available only on the bottom half of the map:

The gear fishers use does not allow them to choose what to catch. If they fish on a tile that has both blue and red fish, they’ll catch both.
The issue is that while the red fish pays 10$ a pound at the dock, the blue fish carries a fine of 50$ a pound. It is extremely expensive to fish blue.

It turns out we don’t need to add anything new to the decision making of the fishers. The same trial and error approach (with imitation through social networks) work “out of the box”. Fishers very quickly learn that staying on the upper side of the map is the safest way not to pay any fine:
